In [[economics]], '''self-revelation''' is a [[Property (philosophy)|property]] of a [[Mechanism (economics)|mechanism]] where each [[Agent (economics)|agent]] maximizes his or her utility (or expected utility) by revealing his or her true type. Self-Revelation is also used as a theme in many literary works. 

Self-revelation is widely used in insurance market. This is when high risk parties and low risk parties choose to pay a different risk premium.

